content:
[1] David and the army commanders set apart the sons of Asaph, Heman, and Jeduthun for service — men who would prophesy with lyres, harps, and cymbals. Here is the roster of those assigned to this work:

[2] From Asaph's sons: Zaccur, Joseph, Nethaniah, and Asarelah — all under their father Asaph, who prophesied at the king's direction.

[3] From Jeduthun's sons: Gedaliah, Zeri, Jeshaiah, Shimei, Hashabiah, and Mattithiah — six in all, under their father Jeduthun, who prophesied with the lyre, giving thanks and praise to the LORD.

[4] From Heman's sons: Bukkiah, Mattaniah, Uzziel, Shebuel, Jerimoth, Hananiah, Hanani, Eliathah, Giddalti, Romamti-Ezer, Joshbekashah, Mallothi, Hothir, and Mahazioth.

[5] All of these were sons of Heman, the king's seer, given to him through the promises of God to lift up his name. God gave Heman fourteen sons and three daughters.

[6] Every one of them served under their father in the music of the LORD's house — cymbals, harps, and lyres ringing out in the service of God's house. Asaph, Jeduthun, and Heman answered directly to the king.

[7] Counting them along with their relatives — every musician trained and skilled in songs for the LORD — the total came to 288.

[8] They cast lots for their duties, small and great alike, teacher and student treated the same.

[9] The first lot fell to Joseph of Asaph's line; the second to Gedaliah — he and his brothers and sons, twelve in all;

[10] the third to Zaccur — his sons and brothers, twelve;

[11] the fourth to Izri — his sons and brothers, twelve;

[12] the fifth to Nethaniah — his sons and brothers, twelve;

[13] the sixth to Bukkiah — his sons and brothers, twelve;

[14] the seventh to Jesharelah — his sons and brothers, twelve;

[15] the eighth to Jeshaiah — his sons and brothers, twelve;

[16] the ninth to Mattaniah — his sons and brothers, twelve;

[17] the tenth to Shimei — his sons and brothers, twelve;

[18] the eleventh to Azarel — his sons and brothers, twelve;

[19] the twelfth to Hashabiah — his sons and brothers, twelve;

[20] the thirteenth to Shubael — his sons and brothers, twelve;

[21] the fourteenth to Mattithiah — his sons and brothers, twelve;

[22] the fifteenth to Jeremoth — his sons and brothers, twelve;

[23] the sixteenth to Hananiah — his sons and brothers, twelve;

[24] the seventeenth to Joshbekashah — his sons and brothers, twelve;

[25] the eighteenth to Hanani — his sons and brothers, twelve;

[26] the nineteenth to Mallothi — his sons and brothers, twelve;

[27] the twentieth to Eliathah — his sons and brothers, twelve;

[28] the twenty-first to Hothir — his sons and brothers, twelve;

[29] the twenty-second to Giddalti — his sons and brothers, twelve;

[30] the twenty-third to Mahazioth — his sons and brothers, twelve;

[31] the twenty-fourth to Romamti-Ezer — his sons and brothers, twelve.

[1] So Solomon ruled all Israel.

[2] These were his top officials:

Azariah son of Zadok—priest;

[3] Elihoreph and Ahijah, sons of Shisha—court secretaries;
Jehoshaphat son of Ahilud—royal historian;

[4] Benaiah son of Jehoiada—commander of the army;
Zadok and Abiathar—priests;

[5] Azariah son of Nathan—head of the district governors;
Zabud son of Nathan—priest and king's confidant;

[6] Ahishar—palace administrator;
Adoniram son of Abda—director of forced labor.

[7] Solomon carved Israel into twelve districts, each one responsible for keeping the king and his household fed for one month a year.

[8] Here are their names:

Ben-Hur—the hill country of Ephraim;

[9] Ben-Deker—Makaz, Shaalbim, Beth-shemesh, and Elon-bethhanan;

[10] Ben-Hesed—Arubboth, including Sokoh and all the land of Hepher;

[11] Ben-Abinadab—the whole region of Dor (he was married to Solomon's daughter Taphath);

[12] Baana son of Ahilud—Taanach and Megiddo, plus all Beth-shean below Jezreel, from Beth-shean to Abel-meholah, stretching past Jokmeam;

[13] Ben-Geber—Ramoth-gilead, including the villages of Jair son of Manasseh in Gilead, and the region of Argob in Bashan—sixty large cities walled with bronze-barred gates;

[14] Ahinadab son of Iddo—Mahanaim;

[15] Ahimaaz—Naphtali (he too married a daughter of Solomon, Basemath);

[16] Baana son of Hushai—Asher and Bealoth;

[17] Jehoshaphat son of Paruah—Issachar;

[18] Shimei son of Ela—Benjamin;

[19] Geber son of Uri—the land of Gilead, the old territory of Sihon king of the Amorites and Og king of Bashan. One governor over the whole region.

[20] Judah and Israel were countless as grains of sand on the seashore—eating, drinking, alive with joy.

[21] Solomon's reach extended over every kingdom from the Euphrates to Philistia, all the way to the Egyptian border. They paid him tribute and bent the knee to him all his days.

[22] His daily provisions: thirty cors of fine flour, sixty cors of meal,

[23] ten stall-fed cattle, twenty pasture-fed cattle, a hundred sheep—plus deer, gazelles, roebucks, and prime fowl.

[24] He held dominion over everything west of the Euphrates, from Tiphsah to Gaza, ruling every king in that region—and he had peace on every side.

[25] Throughout Solomon's reign, every Israelite from Dan to Beersheba sat under his own vine and his own fig tree, unafraid.

[26] Solomon kept forty thousand stalls of horses for his chariots and twelve thousand cavalry.

[27] The district governors kept King Solomon and everyone who dined at his table supplied—each in his assigned month—and they let nothing run short.

[28] They also delivered barley and straw for the horses and chariot teams, hauled to wherever it was needed, each according to his quota.

[29] God gave Solomon wisdom—staggering wisdom—and discernment as wide as the sand on the seashore.

[30] His wisdom outstripped all the wisdom of the East and every sage in Egypt.

[31] He was wiser than anyone—wiser than Ethan the Ezrahite, wiser than Heman, Calcol, and Darda, the sons of Mahol. His fame ran through every nation around.

[32] He composed three thousand proverbs and a thousand and five songs.

[33] He spoke about trees—from the cedar of Lebanon down to the hyssop growing out of a wall. He spoke about animals, birds, reptiles, and fish.

[34] People came from every nation to hear Solomon's wisdom—envoys sent by kings everywhere who'd heard the rumors.

[1] He made a bronze altar—thirty feet long, thirty feet wide, fifteen feet high.

[2] Then he cast the Sea: a massive bronze basin, fifteen feet across rim to rim, perfectly round, seven and a half feet deep, its circumference forty-five feet.

[3] Beneath the rim, two rows of bulls encircled it—ten to every foot and a half—cast as one piece with the basin itself.

[4] The Sea rested on twelve bulls: three facing north, three west, three south, three east, their hindquarters turned inward, the basin riding on their backs.

[5] Its walls were a handsbreadth thick. The rim flared like a cup, shaped like the bloom of a lily. It held eighteen thousand gallons.

[6] He made ten basins as well—five on the right, five on the left—for washing what was used in the burnt offerings. The Sea was for the priests alone, for their own cleansing.

[7] He made ten golden lampstands to the specifications given and set them in the sanctuary, five on the south side, five on the north.

[8] He made ten tables and placed them in the sanctuary, five south, five north. And he made a hundred golden bowls.

[9] He built the courtyard for the priests and the great court beyond it, and overlaid the doors of the great court with bronze.

[10] The Sea he set on the south side, at the southeast corner.

[11] Huram also made the pots, the shovels, the bowls. So Huram finished the work he had undertaken for King Solomon on the house of God:

[12] the two pillars; the bowl-shaped capitals crowning the pillars; the two latticeworks covering those capitals;

[13] the four hundred pomegranates for the two latticeworks—two rows of pomegranates on each lattice, covering the bowl-shaped capitals atop the pillars;

[14] the stands and the basins that rested on them;

[15] the Sea and the twelve bulls beneath it;

[16] the pots, the shovels, the forks, and every related vessel. Huram-abi crafted all of it for King Solomon, for the house of the LORD, in polished bronze.

[17] The king had it all cast in the clay ground of the Jordan valley, between Succoth and Zeredah.

[18] Solomon made these vessels in such staggering quantity that the weight of the bronze could not be calculated.

[19] Solomon also made every furnishing for the house of God: the golden altar; the tables on which the bread of the Presence was set;

[20] the lampstands of pure gold with their lamps, burning before the inner sanctuary as commanded;

[21] the flowers, the lamps, the tongs—gold, the purest gold;

[22] the wick trimmers, the bowls, the dishes, the censers—pure gold; and the doorway of the temple, both the inner doors of the Most Holy Place and the doors of the main hall—gold.

[1] Moses gathered the whole assembly of Israel and said: Here is what the LORD has commanded you to do.

[2] Six days you work. The seventh day is holy — a Sabbath of complete rest, set apart for the LORD. Anyone who works on that day dies.

[3] Do not even kindle a fire in your homes on the Sabbath.

[4] Then Moses said to the entire community of Israel: This is what the LORD has commanded —

[5] Take up an offering for the LORD from what you have. Let everyone with a willing heart bring it: gold, silver, bronze;

[6] blue, purple, and crimson yarn; fine linen, goat hair;

[7] ram skins dyed red, fine leather, acacia wood;

[8] oil for the lamps, spices for the anointing oil and the fragrant incense;

[9] onyx stones and other gems to be set into the ephod and breastpiece.

[10] Every skilled craftsman among you — come and make everything the LORD has commanded:

[11] the Tabernacle itself — its tent, its covering, its clasps, its frames, its crossbars, its posts, its bases;

[12] the Ark with its poles, the atonement cover, and the curtain that screens it;

[13] the table with its poles and all its utensils, and the Bread of the Presence;

[14] the lampstand for light — its lamps, its accessories, its oil;

[15] the altar of incense and its poles, the anointing oil, the fragrant incense, the curtain for the entrance of the Tabernacle;

[16] the altar of burnt offering with its bronze grate, poles, and utensils; the basin and its stand;

[17] the hangings for the courtyard with their posts and bases, and the curtain for the courtyard gate;

[18] the tent pegs for the Tabernacle and the courtyard, with their ropes;

[19] and the finely woven garments for serving in the holy place — the sacred vestments for Aaron the priest and for his sons as they serve.

[20] Then the whole community of Israel left Moses' presence.

[21] And every person whose heart stirred them, every spirit moved to generosity — they came. They brought the LORD's offering for the work on the Tent of Meeting, for all its service, and for the sacred garments.

[22] They came, men and women alike, everyone with a willing heart, bringing brooches, earrings, rings, pendants — every kind of gold ornament. Each one waved their gold before the LORD as an offering.

[23] Everyone who had blue, purple, or crimson yarn, fine linen, goat hair, ram skins dyed red, or fine leather brought it in.

[24] Everyone offering silver or bronze brought it as the LORD's contribution. Everyone with acacia wood useful for the work brought it.

[25] Every skilled woman spun with her own hands and brought what she had spun — blue, purple, crimson yarn, fine linen.

[26] And the women whose hearts moved them, gifted as they were, spun the goat hair.

[27] The leaders brought the onyx stones and the gems for setting in the ephod and breastpiece,

[28] along with the spices and the oil for the light, the anointing oil, and the fragrant incense.

[29] Every man and woman in Israel whose heart moved them brought a freewill offering to the LORD — for all the work the LORD had commanded through Moses to be done.

[30] Then Moses said to the Israelites: Look — the LORD has called by name Bezalel son of Uri, son of Hur, of the tribe of Judah.

[31] He has filled him with the Spirit of God — with wisdom, with understanding, with knowledge, with every kind of skill —

[32] to design intricate work, to craft in gold and silver and bronze,

[33] to cut and set stones, to carve wood, to do every kind of artistic work.

[34] And God has put it in his heart to teach — both him and Oholiab son of Ahisamach, of the tribe of Dan.

[35] He has filled them with skill to do every kind of work — engraver, designer, embroiderer in blue, purple, and crimson yarn and in fine linen, weaver — masters of every craft and visionaries of every design.

[1] The day Moses finished setting up the tabernacle, he anointed it and consecrated it — every part of it, every tool, the altar and all its gear. He anointed them and set them apart as holy.

[2] Then the leaders of Israel stepped forward — the heads of their fathers' houses, the chiefs of the tribes, the men who had overseen the census.

[3] They brought their offering before the LORD: six covered wagons and twelve oxen — a wagon for every two leaders, an ox for each one — and they presented them in front of the tabernacle.

[4] The LORD said to Moses,

[5] "Take them. Use them for the work of the tent of meeting. Distribute them to the Levites — each according to what his service requires."

[6] So Moses took the wagons and the oxen and gave them to the Levites.

[7] To the sons of Gershon he gave two wagons and four oxen — what their service required.

[8] To the sons of Merari he gave four wagons and eight oxen — what their service required, under the direction of Ithamar son of Aaron the priest.

[9] To the sons of Kohath he gave nothing. Their charge was the holy things, which they had to carry on their shoulders.

[10] On the day the altar was anointed, the leaders brought their dedication offerings and set them before the altar.

[11] The LORD said to Moses, "One leader per day. Each one will present his offering for the dedication of the altar."

[12] Day one — Nahshon son of Amminadab, of the tribe of Judah.

[13] His offering: a silver platter weighing 130 shekels, a silver bowl of 70 shekels by the sanctuary standard, both heaped with fine flour mixed with oil for the grain offering;

[14] a gold dish of 10 shekels filled with incense;

[15] a young bull, a ram, and a year-old lamb for the burnt offering;

[16] a male goat for the sin offering;

[17] and for the peace offering — two oxen, five rams, five male goats, five year-old lambs. That was Nahshon's offering.

[18] Day two — Nethanel son of Zuar, leader of Issachar.

[19] He brought: a silver platter of 130 shekels, a silver bowl of 70 by the sanctuary standard, both filled with flour mixed with oil for the grain offering;

[20] a gold dish of 10 shekels full of incense;

[21] a young bull, a ram, a year-old lamb for the burnt offering;

[22] a male goat for sin;

[23] and for peace — two oxen, five rams, five goats, five year-old lambs. That was Nethanel's offering.

[24] Day three — Eliab son of Helon, leader of Zebulun.

[25] His offering: a silver platter of 130 shekels, a silver bowl of 70 by the sanctuary standard, both filled with flour and oil for grain;

[26] a gold dish of 10 shekels of incense;

[27] a young bull, a ram, a year-old lamb for burnt offering;

[28] a male goat for sin;

[29] for peace — two oxen, five rams, five goats, five lambs a year old. Eliab's offering.

[30] Day four — Elizur son of Shedeur, leader of Reuben.

[31] His offering: silver platter, 130 shekels; silver bowl, 70 — both full of flour and oil for grain;

[32] gold dish of 10 shekels, incense;

[33] young bull, ram, year-old lamb — burnt offering;

[34] male goat — sin offering;

[35] peace offering — two oxen, five rams, five goats, five year-old lambs. Elizur's offering.

[36] Day five — Shelumiel son of Zurishaddai, leader of Simeon.

[37] His offering: silver platter, 130 shekels; silver bowl, 70 — both full of flour and oil for grain;

[38] gold dish, 10 shekels, incense;

[39] young bull, ram, year-old lamb — burnt offering;

[40] male goat — sin offering;

[41] peace offering — two oxen, five rams, five goats, five year-old lambs. Shelumiel's offering.

[42] Day six — Eliasaph son of Deuel, leader of Gad.

[43] His offering: silver platter, 130 shekels; silver bowl, 70 — flour and oil for grain;

[44] gold dish, 10 shekels of incense;

[45] young bull, ram, year-old lamb — burnt offering;

[46] male goat — sin offering;

[47] peace offering — two oxen, five rams, five goats, five year-old lambs. Eliasaph's offering.

[48] Day seven — Elishama son of Ammihud, leader of Ephraim.

[49] His offering: silver platter, 130 shekels; silver bowl, 70 — both filled with flour and oil for grain;

[50] gold dish, 10 shekels, incense;

[51] young bull, ram, year-old lamb — burnt offering;

[52] male goat — sin offering;

[53] peace offering — two oxen, five rams, five goats, five year-old lambs. Elishama's offering.

[54] Day eight — Gamaliel son of Pedahzur, leader of Manasseh.

[55] His offering: silver platter, 130 shekels; silver bowl, 70 — flour and oil for grain;

[56] gold dish, 10 shekels of incense;

[57] young bull, ram, year-old lamb — burnt offering;

[58] male goat — sin offering;

[59] peace offering — two oxen, five rams, five goats, five year-old lambs. Gamaliel's offering.

[60] Day nine — Abidan son of Gideoni, leader of Benjamin.

[61] His offering: silver platter, 130 shekels; silver bowl, 70 — flour and oil for grain;

[62] gold dish, 10 shekels, incense;

[63] young bull, ram, year-old lamb — burnt offering;

[64] male goat — sin offering;

[65] peace offering — two oxen, five rams, five goats, five year-old lambs. Abidan's offering.

[66] Day ten — Ahiezer son of Ammishaddai, leader of Dan.

[67] His offering: silver platter, 130 shekels; silver bowl, 70 — flour and oil for grain;

[68] gold dish, 10 shekels of incense;

[69] young bull, ram, year-old lamb — burnt offering;

[70] male goat — sin offering;

[71] peace offering — two oxen, five rams, five goats, five year-old lambs. Ahiezer's offering.

[72] Day eleven — Pagiel son of Ochran, leader of Asher.

[73] His offering: silver platter, 130 shekels; silver bowl, 70 — flour and oil for grain;

[74] gold dish, 10 shekels, incense;

[75] young bull, ram, year-old lamb — burnt offering;

[76] male goat — sin offering;

[77] peace offering — two oxen, five rams, five goats, five year-old lambs. Pagiel's offering.

[78] Day twelve — Ahira son of Enan, leader of Naphtali.

[79] His offering: silver platter, 130 shekels; silver bowl, 70 — flour and oil for grain;

[80] gold dish, 10 shekels of incense;

[81] young bull, ram, year-old lamb — burnt offering;

[82] male goat — sin offering;

[83] peace offering — two oxen, five rams, five goats, five year-old lambs. Ahira's offering.

[84] This was the dedication of the altar from the leaders of Israel on the day it was anointed: twelve silver platters, twelve silver bowls, twelve gold dishes.

[85] Each platter, 130 shekels of silver; each bowl, 70. Total silver from the vessels — 2,400 shekels by the sanctuary standard.

[86] The twelve gold dishes filled with incense — 10 shekels apiece by the sanctuary standard. Total gold: 120 shekels.

[87] All the animals for the burnt offering: twelve bulls, twelve rams, twelve year-old lambs, with their grain offerings; twelve male goats for the sin offering.

[88] For the peace offering: twenty-four oxen, sixty rams, sixty male goats, sixty year-old lambs. That was the dedication of the altar after it was anointed.

[89] And when Moses entered the tent of meeting to speak with him, he heard the voice — speaking to him from above the atonement cover on the ark of the testimony, between the two cherubim. That was how he spoke to him.

[1] The LORD spoke to Moses:

[2] "Command the Israelites: When you cross into Canaan, this is the land falling to you as your inheritance — Canaan, marked out by these borders.

[3] Your southern edge runs from the Wilderness of Zin along the flank of Edom. The southern boundary starts at the eastern end of the Salt Sea,

[4] swings south of the Scorpion Pass, crosses to Zin, ends up south of Kadesh-barnea, then on to Hazar-addar and across to Azmon.

[5] From Azmon it bends to the Wadi of Egypt and runs out to the Sea.

[6] Your western boundary is the Great Sea itself — that coast is your border.

[7] Your northern boundary: from the Great Sea draw a line to Mount Hor,

[8] from Mount Hor to Lebo-hamath, ending at Zedad.

[9] The line pushes on to Ziphron and lands at Hazar-enan. That is your north.

[10] For your eastern boundary, draw a line from Hazar-enan to Shepham.

[11] From Shepham it drops to Riblah on the east side of Ain, then continues down along the eastern slope of the Sea of Chinnereth.

[12] The border follows the Jordan and ends at the Salt Sea. This is your land — this perimeter, these boundaries."

[13] Moses gave the order to the Israelites: "This is the land you will draw by lot as your inheritance, the land the LORD commanded to be given to the nine and a half tribes.

[14] The tribe of Reuben and the tribe of Gad have already claimed their inheritance by clan, and half the tribe of Manasseh has taken theirs.

[15] These two and a half tribes received their land east of the Jordan, opposite Jericho, toward the sunrise."

[16] The LORD said to Moses:

[17] "Here are the men who will apportion the land for you: Eleazar the priest and Joshua son of Nun.

[18] Take one leader from each tribe to oversee the division.

[19] These are their names: from Judah, Caleb son of Jephunneh;

[20] from Simeon, Shemuel son of Ammihud;

[21] from Benjamin, Elidad son of Chislon;

[22] from Dan, Bukki son of Jogli, the leader;

[23] from the sons of Joseph — from Manasseh, Hanniel son of Ephod, the leader;

[24] from Ephraim, Kemuel son of Shiphtan, the leader;

[25] from Zebulun, Elizaphan son of Parnach, the leader;

[26] from Issachar, Paltiel son of Azzan, the leader;

[27] from Asher, Ahihud son of Shelomi, the leader;

[28] from Naphtali, Pedahel son of Ammihud, the leader."

[29] These were the men the LORD appointed to divide the inheritance for the Israelites in the land of Canaan.
